			</td>
			<td valign="top">
				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody">1. Let's take the NES APU sample generation - unsigned samples. The DMC output has an audible hiss caused by a +0x40 factor. Back in old times, the DMC output was <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">value-0x40</tt> to center the wave (signed samples).<br /><br />2. For PC sample generation, well... Allegro uses unsigned samples (16 bits = 2 bytes per sample), and the emulator generates signed samples. Example: the square wave duty cycle  has a volume level (<tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">00-0F</tt>); for signed samples, the zero part becomes a negative sample. So, a duty cycle <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">0 1 1 1 1 1 1 0</tt>, or in volume levels <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">00 0f 0f 0f 0f 0f 0f 00</tt> should output as <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">-0f +0f +0f +0f +0f +0f 0f -0f</tt>. Argh, in other words: <div class="codetitle"><b>Code:</b></div><div class="codecontent">output = 0 != duty ? volume: -volume;</div><br /><br />3. At anyway, the final PC wave is built by <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">value ^ 0x8000</tt> for the Allegro sound wave. I'm not going into this part.</div>

					<br clear="all" /><br />

