				<table width="100%" cellspacing="5">
				<tr>
					<td>
					

						<div class="postbody"><div class="quotetitle">Zepper wrote:</div><div class="quotecontent">1. Let's take the NES APU sample generation - unsigned samples. The DMC output has an audible hiss caused by a +0x40 factor. Back in old times, the DMC output was <tt style="margin-left: 2px; margin-right: 2px; padding:3px; background-color: #3355aa; color: white;">value-0x40</tt> to center the wave (signed samples).</div><br />A constant bias is <em>silent</em>. This does <em>not</em> create &quot;an audible hiss&quot;. There's no &quot;-0x40&quot; or &quot;+0x40&quot; on the output, centering is accomplished with a <em>highpass filter</em>.<br /><br />Either the audible hiss is caused by <em>something else</em>, or something is very broken in your audio output if you think adding or subtracting 64 to the output affects it.</div>

